            "page": "Ozai%27s_airship_base"
          }
        },
        {
          "body": "Wulong Forest",
          "key": "${link_2}",
          "target": {
            "external": false,
            "href": "/wiki/Wulong_Forest",
            "page": "Wulong_Forest"
          }
        }
      ],
      "section": [
        "Royal Procession",
        "History"
      ],
      "text": "Before her coronation as Fire Lord, Azula slipped into a case of severe paranoia and ended up banishing nearly all her staff, including the Imperial Firebenders present at the palace, as mentioned by Lo and Li. Imperial Firebenders were seen as part of the crew of the airship fleet, burning a large section of Wulong Forest and defending the ships from intruders."
    },
    {
      "body": "The members of the Royal Procession wore helmets that had a three-point theme. There were three red spikes on the top of the helmet, three eye holes, and shard-shaped mouth holes. Captains were distinguished by the fact that their helmets had the same general design, but a lack of face masks. When Ozai declared himself the Phoenix King, the uniforms of the members of the Royal Procession were a black inverted version of the original, i.e. whatever was black was red and vice-versa.",
      "links": [],
      "section": [
        "Royal Procession",
        "Uniform"
      ],
      "text": "The members of the Royal Procession wore helmets that had a three-point theme. There were three red spikes on the top of the helmet, three eye holes, and shard-shaped mouth holes. Captains were distinguished by the fact that their helmets had the same general design, but a lack of face masks. When Ozai declared himself the Phoenix King, the uniforms of the members of the Royal Procession were a black inverted version of the original, i.e. whatever was black was red and vice-versa."
    },
    {
      "body": "The bell shaped helmets of the Royal Procession with its extremely small eye holes and mouth holes bear some resemblance to the Italo-Corinthian helmet, a version of the famous Corinthian helmet.",
      "links": [],
      "section": [
